detail_description: Lendi Garden, also known as Lendi Baug, is a colorful and serene garden located near Shirdi-Manmade State Highway. It holds great significance for devotees of Sai Baba, who used to spend time here resting under a Neem tree and watering the plants daily. The garden features a shrine with a burning lamp placed between two trees that were lit by Baba himself.
name: Lendi Garden / Baug
address: QF8G+C9R, MH SH 10, Mauli Nagar, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

excerpt: Museum with photos & personal effects of Sai Baba, a revered 1800s spiritual master & Shirdi native.
detail_description: Dixit Wada Museum, situated within the Shirdi Sai Baba Temple Complex, is a captivating destination for history enthusiasts and devotees of Sai Baba. This charming museum houses rare photographs of Sai Baba and villagers from his era, along with personal items such as his clothing, footwear, smoking pipes, and utensils. Visitors can gain insight into the mystic saint's life and better understand the lifestyle during his time through these intriguing displays.
name: Dixit Wada Museum
address: QF8G+HM4, Mauli Nagar, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

detail_description: Shri Khandoba Mandir is a revered temple located 5 km away from Shirdi, dedicated to the local deity Khandoba, considered a manifestation of Lord Shiva. The temple features two shrines, one housing an idol of Sai Baba with his padukas and the other containing the idol of Lord Khandoba's horse, Shyamsundar. It holds significant historical importance as it used to be an entry point to Shirdi for visitors.
name: Shri Khandoba Mandir
address: QF7G+HCF, Sai Nagar, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

excerpt: Humble mosque & pilgrimage site, once the home of revered religious leader Sai Baba of Shirdi.
detail_description: Dwarkamai Mosque in Shirdi is a humble yet revered pilgrimage site that was once the home of the esteemed religious leader Sai Baba. It is considered one of the holiest places to visit in Shirdi, as it served as Sai Baba's main residence for 60 years. The mosque features the perpetual holy fire, or dhuni, which was first lit by Sai Baba and is believed to have healing powers. Visitors can take wood ash from this fire as a sacred gift.
name: Dwarkamai Shirdi
address: QF8G+CXF, Pimpalwadi Rd, near Vishal textile, opp. Dwarkamai Temple, Mauli Nagar, Rahata, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

excerpt: Landmark village reflecting life during the Sai Baba's time, with historical statues & activities.
detail_description: Sai Heritage Village is a captivating theme park located just a short distance from the bustling Shirdi Sai Baba Temple. Opened in July 2014, this unique destination beautifully intertwines pilgrimage and leisure, offering visitors an immersive experience into the life of Sai Baba and the villagers during his era. As you stroll through the park, you'll encounter intricately crafted statues that depict significant moments from Sai Baba's lifeâ€”such as his acts of kindness towards those in need and scenes reflecting daily village activities.
name: Sai Heritage Village
address: AHMEDNAGAR-MANMAD HIGHWAY SHIRDI, TALUKA, Rahata, Maharashtra 423107, India

excerpt: Temple complex where Indian guru Sai Baba spent his time, featuring a sacred neem tree & festivals.
detail_description: The Shri Sai Baba Temple in Shirdi, Maharashtra, is a significant religious site dedicated to the revered Indian guru Sai Baba. It is considered one of the largest and most important temples in the region, attracting tens of thousands of devotees daily and even more during festivals. Visitors come from all over India to experience the tranquility and spiritual connection associated with this holy place.

name: Chavadi Shirdi
address: QF8H+C36, Shirdi - Puntamba Rd, Mauli Nagar, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

detail_description: Gurusthan, which translates to "seat of the teacher," is a significant site within the Shirdi Sai Baba Temple. It holds great spiritual importance and is located beneath a neem tree near the main temple. Legend has it that this spot is where the remains of Sai Baba's guru were laid to rest, adding to its sanctity and drawing pilgrims and visitors alike.
name: Guru Sthan
address: QF8G+CJQ, Mauli Nagar, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

excerpt: Religious theme park featuring attractions & experiences related to the Hindu faith.
detail_description: Sai Teerth Devotional Theme Park is a unique religious theme park in Shirdi, India, offering a tech-driven and devotional journey through the life of Sai Baba. It features four different shows, including Teerth Yatra showcasing India's impressive temples, Dwarkamai about the mosque where Sai Baba lived, Sab Ka Malik Ek encapsulating the saint's life, and Lanka Dahan providing a 5-D experience of Hanuman's journey to Lanka.
name: Sai Teerth Theme Park
address: QFFG+MM4, opp. to Wet 'nJoy Waterpark, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

detail_description: Haji Abdul Baba's Cottage, located opposite Chavadi in Shirdi, holds great significance as the former residence of Abdul Baba, a devoted patron of Sai Baba. This small prayer house is adorned with old photos and is believed to have been the place where Abdul Baba spent his last years. Visitors can also see a pair of chimta (fire tongs) that were given to him by Sai Baba.
name: Haji Abdul Baba's Cottage.
address: QF8H+93F, Mauli Nagar, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

detail_description: PRO Counter, Shirdi Sai Baba Samadhi Temple is a significant site for visitors to Shirdi. The temple houses the tomb of Sai Baba and features a life-like white marble statue of the saint. Visitors can easily enter with proper paperwork and ID proof, and can complete their darshan within 10-15 minutes. The friendly police near the gate are helpful in providing information about timings and temple guidelines.
name: PRO Counter, Shirdi Sai Baba Samadhi Temple
address: QF8G+Q73, Mauli Nagar, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

detail_description: Gurusthan Nagar is a significant spiritual hub where devotees gather in anticipation of their beloved Baba's arrival. At the crossroads, one can often witness individuals seemingly engaged in conversation, embodying a deep connection to the divine. The atmosphere is filled with devotion as both long-term residents and newcomers line up at the wada, eagerly awaiting their chance for darshan when Baba emerges from the mosque. This vibrant scene captures the essence of faith and community that defines Gurusthan Nagar.
name: Gurusthan Nagar

excerpt: Shirdi is a town in the state of Maharashtra, in western India. It's known as the former home of revered spiritual leader Sai Baba, and as a major pilgrimage site. Devotees gather daily at the Sai Baba Temple complex to honor his legacy. Here, the Samadhi Mandir shrine has an ornate marble statue of Sai Baba, alongside his tomb. Close by are Dwarkamai, a mosque where Sai Baba once lived, and tree-lined Lendi Garden.
detail_description: Shirdi, located in Maharashtra, India, is a significant pilgrimage site and the former home of revered spiritual leader Sai Baba. The town is known for the Sai Baba Temple complex, where devotees gather daily to honor his legacy. The complex includes the ornate marble statue of Sai Baba at the Samadhi Mandir shrine, his tomb, Dwarkamai mosque where he once lived, and tree-lined Lendi Garden.
name: Shirdi
address: Maharashtra, India

detail_description: The Hanuman Temple offers free bus services that run regularly from various accommodations to Prasadalaya via the temple. Devotees can partake in yearly meals at the temple and experience the divine magic of God firsthand. It's a place where visitors are encouraged to witness and feel the spiritual energy for themselves.
name: Hanuman Temple
address: QFC8+WMP, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

detail_description: Hanuman Mandir, also known as Maruti Mandir, is one of the oldest temples in Shirdi. It stands out for its unique orientation facing south and features two idols of Hanuman alongside a few dumbbells in a corner, symbolizing his strength. This temple holds historical significance as it used to be inhabited by sadhus and was occasionally visited by Baba during his early days in Shirdi.
name: hanuman mandir Sai Vitthala nagar
address: QF77+4FV, sai Vitthala nagar, Govind Nagar, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

excerpt: Temple complex where Indian guru Sai Baba spent his time, featuring a sacred neem tree & festivals.
detail_description: Shri Sai Baba Temple Shirdi is a temple complex where the revered Indian guru, Sai Baba, spent much of his time. The site features a sacred neem tree and hosts various festivals. Chavadi, once used as a town hall, has been transformed into a museum displaying personal belongings of Sai Baba. Visitors can also explore the Dwarkamai Mosque nearby, where devotees still carry out processions with the idol of Sai Baba every Thursday.
name: Shri Sai Baba Temple Shirdi
address: Mauli Nagar, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

excerpt: Development offices for a major Hindu pilgrimage site , managing daily activities, lodgings & meals.
detail_description: Shri Saibaba Sansthan Trust in Shirdi is a major Hindu pilgrimage site that manages daily activities, accommodations, and meals for pilgrims. The temple, covering 200 square meters, is a central attraction in Shirdi and draws pilgrims from around the world. It offers accommodation for visitors and is open from 5 a.m. to 11 p.m., with special overnight openings on occasions like Guru Purnima and Rama Navami.
name: Shri Saibaba Sansthan Trust, Shirdi
address: Nagar-Manmad Highway near Sai Complex Shirdi Tal. Rahata, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

detail_description: Nanda Deep is a perpetual lamp located in the garden, between a neem tree and a Bodhi tree. It is believed to have been first lit by Shiridi Sai Baba and continues to burn continuously. Visitors find it very auspicious to witness this sacred lamp and perform parikrama around it. Additionally, the Dixit Wada Museum in Shirdi houses an intriguing collection of old photographs and rare collectibles related to the saint, making it a pleasant place for visitors to explore.
name: Nanda Deep.
address: QF8G+MG4, Shirdi - Puntamba Rd, Mauli Nagar, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India

excerpt: Temple to guru Sai Baba, providing free meals to devotees from a solar-powered kitchen.
detail_description: Prasadalaya in Shirdi is a remarkable temple facility dedicated to the revered Sai Baba, where spiritual and culinary experiences intertwine. This unique dining hall can accommodate up to 150 devotees at once, offering delicious meals prepared from locally sourced ingredients. For a nominal fee of INR 10, visitors can savor divine prasad that reflects the essence of local cuisine. The kitchen operates on solar power, emphasizing sustainability while serving thousands daily with love and devotion.

address: New Prasadalaya Rd, Shirdi, Maharashtra 423109, India
